---
import SlidesLayout from '../../../layouts/SlidesLayout.astro';
const base = (import.meta.env.BASE_URL || '').replace(/\/$/, '');
---

<SlidesLayout
  title="COPD Exacerbation — Worked Concept Map Example – Slides – Encyclopedia"
  protected={true}
  backHref={`${base}/private/encyclopedia/nursing-concept-map-copd-example`}
  backLabel="← Full Article"
>

  <!--
    Slide structure follows docs/slides-design-standards.md:
      • Each .slide-column holds one main slide (row 0) and optional slides (row 1+).
      • Horizontal (→) moves between columns (main slides).
      • Vertical (↓) moves to optional sub-slides within a column.
      • Right arrow from an optional slide skips to the next MAIN slide.
  -->

  <div class="slides-wrapper">

    <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
    <!-- COLUMN 1 · Title (main only)                                  -->
    <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
    <div class="slide-column">
      <div class="column-inner">
        <div class="slide slide-title">
          <div class="slide-badge">Encyclopedia – Nursing · Worked Example</div>
          <div class="title-icon">🫁</div>
          <h1 class="slide-main-title">COPD Exacerbation</h1>
          <h2 class="slide-subtitle">Worked Concept Map Example</h2>
          <div class="patient-pill">
            <span>👤 Mr. James Holloway · 68 M · GOLD Stage III COPD</span>
          </div>
          <div class="phase-row">
            {['1','2','3','4','5','6','7'].map((num, i) => {
              const labels = ['Data Collection','Data Organisation','Clinical Reasoning','Goal Setting','Intervention Planning','Drawing Connections','Evaluation'];
              return (
                <div class="phase-badge-item">
                  <span class="phase-num">{num}</span>
                  <span class="phase-label">{labels[i]}</span>
                </div>
              );
            })}
          </div>
          <p class="slide-note">← → Arrow keys or Prev / Next buttons to navigate · ↓ Arrow key for optional detail slides</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
    <!-- COLUMN 2 · Case Overview (main + optional: diagnostics)       -->
    <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
    <div class="slide-column">
      <div class="column-inner">

        <!-- Main slide -->
        <div class="slide">
          <div class="slide-number">2 / 10</div>
          <h2 class="slide-heading">Case Overview — Mr. James Holloway</h2>
          <p class="slide-intro">68-year-old male admitted from ED with <strong>2-day history of worsening dyspnoea</strong>, productive cough, and increased sputum. Admitting diagnosis: <strong>Acute exacerbation of COPD (GOLD III)</strong> — likely viral trigger; rule out community-acquired pneumonia.</p>
          <div class="two-col">
            <div class="col-card">
              <h3 class="col-title">Patient History</h3>
              <ul class="bullet-list">
                <li>🚬 45 pack-year smoking history (quit 5 years ago)</li>
                <li>📋 PMH: COPD (GOLD III), hypertension, T2DM, chronic low back pain</li>
                <li>⚠️ Allergy: Penicillin (rash)</li>
                <li>💊 3-week lapse in tiotropium due to cost concerns</li>
                <li>Home medications: tiotropium, salmeterol/fluticasone, metformin, lisinopril, ibuprofen PRN</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="col-card">
              <h3 class="col-title">Admission Vital Signs</h3>
              <ul class="bullet-list">
                <li>🌡️ Temp 37.9 °C (100.2 °F)</li>
                <li>❤️ HR 108 bpm (sinus tachycardia)</li>
                <li>🫁 RR 28 breaths/min</li>
                <li>🩸 BP 158/92 mmHg</li>
                <li>📊 SpO₂ <strong>84% on room air</strong> → 90% on 2 L/min NC</li>
                <li>Patient reports dyspnoea <strong>8/10</strong> at rest</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="callout callout-warning">
            ⚠️ SpO₂ 84% + RR 28 + accessory muscle use = <strong>immediate life threat</strong> — prioritise Airway &amp; Breathing.
          </div>
          <div class="optional-hint">
            <span class="arrow">↓</span>
            <span>Diagnostic results &amp; respiratory assessment</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Optional slide: diagnostics -->
        <div class="slide optional">
          <div class="back-hint">
            <span class="arrow">↑</span>
            <span>Back to Case Overview</span>
          </div>
          <div class="opt-inner">
            <h2 class="slide-heading">Diagnostic Results &amp; Respiratory Assessment</h2>
            <p class="slide-intro">Key objective findings that drive nursing diagnosis formulation.</p>
            <div class="two-col">
              <div class="col-card">
                <h3 class="col-title">Arterial Blood Gas (2 L/min NC)</h3>
                <ul class="bullet-list">
                  <li>pH <strong>7.32</strong> (↓ acidotic)</li>
                  <li>PaCO₂ <strong>58 mmHg</strong> (↑ CO₂ retention)</li>
                  <li>PaO₂ <strong>58 mmHg</strong> (↓ hypoxaemia)</li>
                  <li>HCO₃ <strong>30 mEq/L</strong> (↑ renal compensation)</li>
                  <li>→ Partially compensated <strong>respiratory acidosis</strong></li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <div class="col-card">
                <h3 class="col-title">Labs, CXR &amp; Physical Exam</h3>
                <ul class="bullet-list">
                  <li>WBC <strong>13.4 × 10³/µL</strong> (neutrophil predominance)</li>
                  <li>CXR: hyperinflation, flattened diaphragms, <strong>RLL infiltrate</strong></li>
                  <li>Barrel chest, prolonged expiratory phase, audible wheeze</li>
                  <li>Diffuse coarse crackles bilaterally; accessory muscle use at rest</li>
                  <li>Central cyanosis at lips; diaphoresis; capillary refill 3 s</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="callout" style="margin-top:1rem;">
              📋 Wife reports patient was confused and "not himself" last evening — likely transient hypoxia-driven encephalopathy. Now GCS 15.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
    <!-- COLUMN 3 · Phase 1: Data Collection (main + optional)         -->
    <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
    <div class="slide-column">
      <div class="column-inner">

        <!-- Main slide -->
        <div class="slide">
          <div class="slide-number">3 / 10</div>
          <h2 class="slide-heading"><span class="phase-circle">1</span> Data Collection (Assessment)</h2>
          <p class="slide-intro">The student nurse reviews Mr. Holloway's chart before entering, then conducts a systematic head-to-toe assessment. Key cues clustered from this data will drive every subsequent phase.</p>
          <div class="two-col">
            <div class="col-card">
              <h3 class="col-title">Objective Data Highlights</h3>
              <ul class="bullet-list">
                <li>SpO₂ 84% RA → 90% on 2 L/min NC; RR 28/min</li>
                <li>Barrel chest; accessory muscle use; pursed-lip breathing</li>
                <li>Prolonged expiration; audible expiratory wheeze</li>
                <li>Coarse bilateral crackles; ↓ breath sounds lower lobes</li>
                <li>Mild central cyanosis; diaphoresis; HR 108</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="col-card">
              <h3 class="col-title">Subjective Data Highlights</h3>
              <ul class="bullet-list">
                <li>"I can't catch my breath no matter what I do."</li>
                <li>Dyspnoea 8/10 at rest; unable to complete a sentence</li>
                <li>Sputum changed from white → yellow-green ~48 hours ago</li>
                <li>Cannot sleep lying flat; sleeping in recliner × 2 nights</li>
                <li>3-week tiotropium lapse due to cost concerns</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="callout callout-tip">
            ✅ Medication reconciliation flag: 3-week lapse in tiotropium (long-acting anticholinergic) identified as a <strong>modifiable precipitant</strong> — links to Deficient Knowledge.
          </div>
          <div class="optional-hint">
            <span class="arrow">↓</span>
            <span>COPD-specific assessment considerations</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Optional slide: COPD-specific assessment tips -->
        <div class="slide optional">
          <div class="back-hint">
            <span class="arrow">↑</span>
            <span>Back to Phase 1</span>
          </div>
          <div class="opt-inner">
            <h2 class="slide-heading">Phase 1 – COPD-Specific Assessment Considerations</h2>
            <p class="slide-intro">Chronic lung disease produces findings that differ from acute-onset respiratory failure — recognise baseline vs. acute change.</p>
            <div class="two-col">
              <div class="col-card">
                <h3 class="col-title">Chronic COPD Baseline Cues</h3>
                <ul class="bullet-list">
                  <li><strong>Barrel chest</strong> — chronic air-trapping, increased AP diameter</li>
                  <li><strong>Pursed-lip breathing</strong> — spontaneous adaptation to ↑ expiratory resistance</li>
                  <li><strong>Elevated HCO₃</strong> — chronic renal compensation for CO₂ retention</li>
                  <li>Chronic wheeze and ↓ breath sounds — not necessarily new</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <div class="col-card">
                <h3 class="col-title">Acute Exacerbation Cues (New / Worsening)</h3>
                <ul class="bullet-list">
                  <li>↑ Dyspnoea from baseline; dyspnoea at rest (new)</li>
                  <li>Sputum colour change to yellow-green (infection signal)</li>
                  <li>SpO₂ below patient's usual baseline</li>
                  <li>↑ RR, accessory muscle use at rest, new cyanosis</li>
                  <li>pH ↓ below 7.35 despite chronic compensation</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
    <!-- COLUMN 4 · Phase 2: Data Organisation (main + optional)       -->
    <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
    <div class="slide-column">
      <div class="column-inner">

        <!-- Main slide -->
        <div class="slide">
          <div class="slide-number">4 / 10</div>
          <h2 class="slide-heading"><span class="phase-circle">2</span> Data Organisation</h2>
          <p class="slide-intro">The student nurse groups Mr. Holloway's findings into <strong>six clinical clusters</strong>, each pointing toward a distinct nursing diagnosis. Separating medical from nursing diagnoses clarifies the independent nursing role.</p>
          <div class="three-col">
            <div class="col-card col-card-sm">
              <h3 class="col-title col-title-sm">🔴 Cluster 1 – Gas Exchange</h3>
              <p class="col-body">SpO₂ 84% RA / 90% NC; RR 28; pH 7.32; PaCO₂ 58; PaO₂ 58; accessory muscle use; central cyanosis; wheeze; prolonged expiration</p>
              <p class="col-example">→ Impaired Gas Exchange</p>
            </div>
            <div class="col-card col-card-sm">
              <h3 class="col-title col-title-sm">🔴 Cluster 2 – Airway</h3>
              <p class="col-body">Coarse bilateral crackles; ↓ breath sounds lower lobes; productive cough with yellow-green sputum; WBC 13.4; RLL infiltrate; temp 37.9 °C</p>
              <p class="col-example">→ Ineffective Airway Clearance</p>
            </div>
            <div class="col-card col-card-sm">
              <h3 class="col-title col-title-sm">🟠 Cluster 3 – Activity</h3>
              <p class="col-body">Cannot complete a sentence; diaphoresis; HR 108 at rest; orthopnoea × 2 nights; dyspnoea 8/10</p>
              <p class="col-example">→ Activity Intolerance</p>
            </div>
            <div class="col-card col-card-sm">
              <h3 class="col-title col-title-sm">🟡 Cluster 4 – Anxiety</h3>
              <p class="col-body">Agitation when answering questions; distress; wife reports confusion last evening; "I can't catch my breath"</p>
              <p class="col-example">→ Anxiety</p>
            </div>
            <div class="col-card col-card-sm">
              <h3 class="col-title col-title-sm">🟢 Cluster 5 – Knowledge</h3>
              <p class="col-body">3-week tiotropium lapse due to cost; 45 pack-year history; 2-day delay before seeking care</p>
              <p class="col-example">→ Deficient Knowledge</p>
            </div>
            <div class="col-card col-card-sm">
              <h3 class="col-title col-title-sm">🟢 Cluster 6 – Infection</h3>
              <p class="col-body">Yellow-green sputum; WBC 13.4; RLL infiltrate; sputum culture pending; penicillin allergy</p>
              <p class="col-example">→ Risk for Infection (worsening)</p>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="optional-hint">
            <span class="arrow">↓</span>
            <span>Medical vs. nursing diagnosis distinction</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Optional slide: medical vs nursing diagnosis -->
        <div class="slide optional">
          <div class="back-hint">
            <span class="arrow">↑</span>
            <span>Back to Phase 2</span>
          </div>
          <div class="opt-inner">
            <h2 class="slide-heading">Phase 2 – Medical vs. Nursing Diagnosis</h2>
            <p class="slide-intro">Separating these domains clarifies <em>what the nurse can independently address</em> vs. what requires a physician order.</p>
            <div class="two-col">
              <div class="col-card">
                <h3 class="col-title">Medical Diagnosis (Physician)</h3>
                <ul class="bullet-list">
                  <li>Acute exacerbation of COPD (GOLD III)</li>
                  <li>Possible community-acquired pneumonia</li>
                  <li>Respiratory acidosis</li>
                  <li>→ Physician treats the <em>disease process</em></li>
                  <li>Nurse administers dependent interventions (O₂, bronchodilators, antibiotics) per orders</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <div class="col-card">
                <h3 class="col-title">Nursing Diagnoses (Nurse)</h3>
                <ul class="bullet-list">
                  <li>Address Mr. Holloway's <em>human responses</em> to his disease</li>
                  <li>Impaired Gas Exchange — the nurse can independently reposition, coach PLB, titrate O₂ within ordered parameters</li>
                  <li>Deficient Knowledge — the nurse can teach, provide resources, involve social work</li>
                  <li>Anxiety — the nurse can apply fan therapy, coach breathing, provide presence</li>
                  <li>→ Nurse has <strong>independent scope</strong> for all six diagnoses</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
    <!-- COLUMN 5 · Phase 3: Clinical Reasoning & Nursing Dx           -->
    <!--            (main + optional: PES statements)                  -->
    <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
    <div class="slide-column">
      <div class="column-inner">

        <!-- Main slide -->
        <div class="slide">
          <div class="slide-number">5 / 10</div>
          <h2 class="slide-heading"><span class="phase-circle">3</span> Clinical Reasoning &amp; Nursing Diagnoses</h2>
          <p class="slide-intro">Six nursing diagnoses formulated using NANDA-I PES format and prioritised by ABC framework then Maslow's Hierarchy.</p>
          <div class="dx-list">
            {[
              { pri: '🔴 1', dx: 'Impaired Gas Exchange', rt: 'ventilation-perfusion mismatch &amp; alveolar hypoventilation secondary to COPD exacerbation', aeb: 'SpO₂ 84% RA, pH 7.32, PaCO₂ 58, central cyanosis, RR 28, accessory muscle use' },
              { pri: '🔴 2', dx: 'Ineffective Airway Clearance', rt: 'excessive mucus &amp; bronchospasm secondary to COPD exacerbation &amp; probable pneumonia', aeb: 'coarse bilateral crackles, yellow-green sputum, ↓ breath sounds bilateral lower lobes, RLL infiltrate' },
              { pri: '🟠 3', dx: 'Activity Intolerance', rt: 'imbalance between O₂ supply and demand', aeb: 'unable to complete a sentence, diaphoresis, HR 108 at rest, dyspnoea 8/10' },
              { pri: '🟡 4', dx: 'Anxiety', rt: 'acute dyspnoea &amp; fear of suffocation', aeb: 'agitation, distress during conversation, "I can\'t catch my breath"' },
              { pri: '🟢 5', dx: 'Deficient Knowledge', rt: 'COPD self-management &amp; inhaler adherence', aeb: '3-week tiotropium lapse due to cost; 2-day delay before seeking care' },
              { pri: '🟢 6', dx: 'Risk for Infection (progression)', rt: 'secretion stasis, bacterial superinfection; penicillin allergy limits antibiotic options', aeb: 'risk diagnosis — no AEB required' },
            ].map(({ pri, dx, rt, aeb }) => (
              <div class="dx-row">
                <span class="dx-pri" set:html={pri} />
                <div>
                  <strong class="dx-name">{dx}</strong>
                  <span class="dx-detail">R/T <span set:html={rt} /> AEB {aeb}</span>
                </div>
              </div>
            ))}
          </div>
          <div class="optional-hint">
            <span class="arrow">↓</span>
            <span>Prioritisation rationale</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Optional slide: prioritisation rationale -->
        <div class="slide optional">
          <div class="back-hint">
            <span class="arrow">↑</span>
            <span>Back to Phase 3</span>
          </div>
          <div class="opt-inner">
            <h2 class="slide-heading">Phase 3 – Prioritisation Rationale</h2>
            <p class="slide-intro">The student nurse applies both ABC and Maslow's Hierarchy to justify the priority order.</p>
            <div class="two-col">
              <div class="col-card">
                <h3 class="col-title">ABC Framework</h3>
                <ul class="bullet-list">
                  <li>🔴 <strong>Dx 1 — Impaired Gas Exchange</strong>: SpO₂ 84% + respiratory acidosis = immediate life threat. Must be addressed first and most aggressively.</li>
                  <li>🔴 <strong>Dx 2 — Ineffective Airway Clearance</strong>: Retained secretions worsen gas exchange — treating Dx 2 is a direct intervention on Dx 1.</li>
                  <li>🟠 <strong>Dx 3 — Activity Intolerance</strong>: Downstream of oxygenation; will improve as Dx 1 is addressed.</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <div class="col-card">
                <h3 class="col-title">Maslow &amp; Clinical Reasoning</h3>
                <ul class="bullet-list">
                  <li>🟡 <strong>Dx 4 — Anxiety</strong>: Attended to concurrently — unmanaged anxiety ↑ O₂ demand and worsens dyspnoea. Non-pharmacological first (fan therapy, PLB).</li>
                  <li>🟢 <strong>Dx 5 — Deficient Knowledge</strong>: Important but deferred — teaching is unsafe when patient is dyspnoeic at 84% SpO₂.</li>
                  <li>🟢 <strong>Dx 6 — Risk for Infection</strong>: Monitor closely; antibiotic selection constrained by penicillin allergy.</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="callout callout-tip" style="margin-top:1rem;">
              🧠 Student reflection: "I had to resist the urge to teach about inhalers first — the most obvious preventable cause — but fixing the gas exchange problem first is what creates the conditions for safe teaching."
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
    <!-- COLUMN 6 · Phase 4: Goal & Outcome Setting (main + optional)  -->
    <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
    <div class="slide-column">
      <div class="column-inner">

        <!-- Main slide -->
        <div class="slide">
          <div class="slide-number">6 / 10</div>
          <h2 class="slide-heading"><span class="phase-circle">4</span> Goal &amp; Outcome Setting</h2>
          <p class="slide-intro">SMART outcomes written for Mr. Holloway — patient-centred, measurable, and time-bound. Note the COPD-specific oxygen target.</p>
          <div class="goal-list">
            {[
              { dx: 'Dx 1 — Impaired Gas Exchange', goal: 'Maintain SpO₂ ≥ 90% on ≤ 4 L/min NC and report dyspnoea ≤ 4/10 at rest within 4 hours of initiating bronchodilator + O₂ therapy.', note: '⚠️ COPD target SpO₂ 88–92% (not 94–98%) — avoid suppressing hypoxic drive' },
              { dx: 'Dx 2 — Ineffective Airway Clearance', goal: 'Demonstrate effective airway clearance evidenced by thin, clear-to-white sputum and improved auscultation within 24–48 hours.', note: '' },
              { dx: 'Dx 3 — Activity Intolerance', goal: 'Tolerate sitting at the edge of the bed × 5 min without SpO₂ < 88% or dyspnoea > 5/10, within 48 hours.', note: '' },
              { dx: 'Dx 4 — Anxiety', goal: 'Report anxiety ≤ 3/10 and demonstrate reduced agitation within 1 hour of non-pharmacological anxiolytic interventions.', note: '⚠️ Benzodiazepines carry respiratory depression risk in COPD — non-pharmacological first' },
              { dx: 'Dx 5 — Deficient Knowledge', goal: 'Verbally identify purpose of each inhaler, correct sequence, three COPD warning signs, and two medication cost resources before discharge.', note: '' },
              { dx: 'Dx 6 — Risk for Infection', goal: 'Remain free of infection progression signs (WBC trending ↓, temp ≤ 37.5 °C, no new sputum changes) throughout hospitalisation.', note: '' },
            ].map(({ dx, goal, note }) => (
              <div class="goal-row">
                <strong class="goal-dx">{dx}</strong>
                <span class="goal-text">{goal}</span>
                {note && <span class="goal-note">{note}</span>}
              </div>
            ))}
          </div>
          <div class="optional-hint">
            <span class="arrow">↓</span>
            <span>Oxygen target rationale for COPD</span>
          </div>
        </div>

        <!-- Optional slide: O2 target rationale -->
        <div class="slide optional">
          <div class="back-hint">
            <span class="arrow">↑</span>
            <span>Back to Phase 4</span>
          </div>
          <div class="opt-inner">
            <h2 class="slide-heading">Phase 4 – COPD Oxygen Target Rationale</h2>
            <p class="slide-intro">The oxygen goal for Mr. Holloway differs from most patients — a critical COPD clinical pearl.</p>
            <div class="two-col">
              <div class="col-card">
                <h3 class="col-title">Why 88–92%, Not 94–98%?</h3>
                <ul class="bullet-list">
                  <li>Patients with <strong>chronic CO₂ retention</strong> (PaCO₂ chronically elevated) may rely on <em>hypoxic drive</em> to stimulate breathing</li>
                  <li>Mr. Holloway's HCO₃ 30 mEq/L = chronic renal compensation → baseline hypercapnia confirmed</li>
                  <li>Excessive O₂ can blunt hypoxic drive → <strong>↑ PaCO₂ → CO₂ narcosis → respiratory failure</strong></li>
                  <li>Target SpO₂ 88–92% per GOLD guidelines and COPD-specific protocols</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <div class="col-card">
                <h3 class="col-title">Clinical Application</h3>
                <ul class="bullet-list">
                  <li>Document the target SpO₂ range <strong>explicitly</strong> in the care plan</li>
                  <li>Titrate O₂ to the <em>minimum</em> flow that achieves 88–92%</li>
                  <li>Monitor for ↑ PaCO₂ despite improving SpO₂ — rising PaCO₂ = worsening hypoventilation</li>
                  <li>If SpO₂ drops below 88% — notify physician immediately; do not simply turn up O₂</li>
                  <li>ABG monitoring is essential to guide therapy decisions</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
    <!-- COLUMN 7 · Phase 5: Intervention Planning (main + optional)   -->
    <!-- ══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
    <div class="slide-column">
      <div class="column-inner">

        <!-- Main slide -->
        <div class="slide">
          <div class="slide-number">7 / 10</div>
          <h2 class="slide-heading"><span class="phase-circle">5</span> Intervention Planning</h2>
          <p class="slide-intro">Evidence-based interventions for each nursing diagnosis — categorised as independent, dependent, or collaborative.</p>
          <div class="two-col">
            <div class="col-card">
              <h3 class="col-title">Dx 1 — Impaired Gas Exchange</h3>
              <ul class="bullet-list">
                <li>🟢 <strong>Independent:</strong> High Fowler's / 30–45° HOB; coach pursed-lip breathing; continuous SpO₂ monitoring; hourly neuro checks for CO₂ narcosis</li>
                <li>🔵 <strong>Dependent:</strong> O₂ titrated to SpO₂ 88–92%; nebulised albuterol/ipratropium; IV methylprednisolone per order</li>
                <li>🟡 <strong>Collaborative:</strong> Respiratory therapy; notify physician if SpO₂ &lt; 88% or worsening mental status</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
            <div class="col-card">
              <h3 class="col-title">Dx 2 — Ineffective Airway Clearance</h3>
              <ul class="bullet-list">
                <li>🟢 <strong>Independent:</strong> Encourage oral hydration; teach huff coughing; reposition q2h; auscultate post-coughing</li>
                <li>🔵 <strong>Dependent:</strong> Antibiotic administration per sensitivity (confirm penicillin allergy; avoid beta-lactam cross-reactivity)</li>
                <li>🟡 <strong>Collaborative:</strong> Respiratory therapy for chest physio / OPEP device; report sputum changes</li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="callout callout-tip">
            ✅ Pursed-lip breathing is an <strong>independent</strong> intervention — no order required. It prolongs exhalation, reduces air-trapping, and has evidence-based support for ↑ SpO₂ and ↓ dyspnoea.
          </div>
          <div class="optional-hint">
            <span class="arrow">↓</span>
            <span>Interventions for Dx 3–6</span>
          </div>
